<div class="page-anchor-wrapper"><a class="record-pageview" name="page-2" data-page="2" data-url="https://arstechnica.com/culture/2024/10/celebrate-halloween-with-20-of-our-favorite-horror-comedies/"></a></div>
<h2><em>Little Shop of Horrors</em> (1986)</h2>
<figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2058873 align-none">
    <div>
                        <div class="ars-lightbox">
            <div class="ars-lightbox-item">
              <a data-pswp-width="1200" data-pswp-height="804" data-pswp-srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror5-300x201.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror5-640x429.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror5-768x515.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror5-980x657.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror5.jpg 1200w" data-cropped="true" href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror5.jpg" target="_blank" class="cursor-zoom-in">
                <img decoding="async" width="1200" height="804" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror5.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full" alt="giant green carnivorous plant with mouth lined with sharp teeth has a young blonde woman in its grasp" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror5.jpg 1200w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror5-300x201.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror5-640x429.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror5-768x515.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror5-980x657.jpg 980w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px">
              </a>
              <div class="pswp-caption-content" id="caption-2058873">
                
                                  <div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit">
                    Credit:
                                          Warner Bros.
                                      </div>
                              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
                  </div>
                  <figcaption>
          <div class="caption font-impact mb-4 mt-2 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-base leading-tight text-gray-300">
    <div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_7px] w-[10px] shrink-0"></div>
    <div class="caption-content">
      

              <span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs">
          Credit:

          
          Warner Bros.

                  </span>
          </div>
  </div>
        </figcaption>
            </figure>

<p>This one is an adaptation of a hit off-Broadway musical that was, in turn, an adaptation of the 1960 horror comedy directed by Roger Corman. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Little_Shop_of_Horrors_(1986_film)"><em>Little Shop of Horrors</em></a> stars Rick Moranis as Seymour Krelborn, a floral shop employee in love with his co-worker, Audrey (Ellen Greene), who is also being pursued by a sadistic dentist addicted to nitrous oxide (Steve Martin). The discovery of an exotic sentient plant that Seymour names Audrey II helps boost business, but Seymour discovers it needs human flesh and blood to survive... and the bigger the insatiable Audrey II grows, the more blood she needs ("Feed me, Seymour!").</p>
<p>Director Frank Oz used animatronic puppetry to create Audrey II, eschewing blue screens or other visual effects. He wasn't particularly happy with his final Oscar-nominated film, mostly because the studio forced him to scrap the musical's original ending, in which Seymour and Audrey both die and Audrey II and her alien plant offspring ravage the Earth. Critics and audiences didn't mind the more upbeat ending, however, no doubt won over by the catchy tunes and deft mix of campy humor and horror.</p>
<h2><em>Evil Dead II</em> (1987)</h2>
<figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2058876 align-none">
    <div>
                        <div class="ars-lightbox">
            <div class="ars-lightbox-item">
              <a data-pswp-width="1200" data-pswp-height="809" data-pswp-srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror6-300x202.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror6-640x431.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror6-768x518.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror6-980x661.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror6.jpg 1200w" data-cropped="true" href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror6.jpg" target="_blank" class="cursor-zoom-in">
                <img decoding="async" width="1200" height="809" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror6.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full" alt="Dark haired man, covered in blood, holding a chainsaw while skeleton hands reach for him" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror6.jpg 1200w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror6-300x202.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror6-640x431.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror6-768x518.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror6-980x661.jpg 980w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px">
              </a>
              <div class="pswp-caption-content" id="caption-2058876">
                This franchise made Bruce Campbell a horror-comedy icon.
                                  <div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit">
                    Credit:
                                          Renaissance Pictures
                                      </div>
                              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
                  </div>
                  <figcaption>
          <div class="caption font-impact mb-4 mt-2 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-base leading-tight text-gray-300">
    <div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_5px] w-[10px] shrink-0"></div>
    <div class="caption-content">
      This franchise made Bruce Campbell a horror-comedy icon.

              <span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs">
          Credit:

          
          Renaissance Pictures

                  </span>
          </div>
  </div>
        </figcaption>
            </figure>

<p>Sam Raimi's blood-soaked trilogy made Bruce Campbell a horror icon, and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evil_Dead_II"><em>Evil Dead II</em></a> is arguably the best of the lot (although I also have a soft spot for <em>Army of Darkness</em>). Whether it's a remake of the original <em>Evil Dead</em> or a sequel is a matter of debate; honestly, it's a bit of both. Campbell stars as Ash Williams, a college student who takes his girlfriend on a romantic getaway to an abandoned cabin in the woods. They discover that the former owner, an archaeologist, left behind a "book of the dead" (<em>Necronomicon Ex-Mortis</em>) and commit the fatal error of reading some of the passages out loud.</p>
<p>This unleashes a Kandarian Demon that kills and possesses his girlfriend, turning her into a "Deadite." Ash is forced to decapitate her and ends up battling multiple Deadite victims of the demon, cutting off his own arm when his right hand becomes possessed. The moment when a blooded Ash straps a modified chainsaw to the stump and mows down a bunch of deadites is a scene for the ages. It's got a rough, low-budget energy, smirking humor, and enough blood and gore to fuel three average horror movies—a bona fide "comedy of terrors."</p>

          
                  </div>

              </div>

      
      <div class="hidden min-w-[300px] justify-self-end bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-50 lg:block">
        
                  <div class="ad-wrapper is-sticky is-rail">
        <div class="ad-wrapper-inner">
            <div class="ad ad--rail"></div>
        </div>
    </div>
              </div>
    </div>
                    
        <div class="ad-wrapper with-label is-fullwidth">
        <div class="ad-wrapper-inner">
            <div class="ad ad--mid-content">
          </div>
        </div>
    </div>
          
    
    <div class="mx-auto my-2.5 px-[15px] sm:px-5 lg:grid lg:max-w-5xl lg:grid-cols-3 lg:gap-6 lg:px-8 xl:px-0">
      <div class="relative lg:col-span-2">

        
        <div class="post-content post-content-double">
          
          
<h2><em>Tremors</em> (1990)</h2>
<figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-1643287 align-none">
    <div>
                        <div class="ars-lightbox">
            <div class="ars-lightbox-item">
              <a data-pswp-width="1200" data-pswp-height="795" data-pswp-srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/tremors16-300x199.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/tremors16-640x424.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/tremors16-768x509.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/tremors16-980x649.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/tremors16.jpg 1200w" data-cropped="true" href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/tremors16.jpg" target="_blank" class="cursor-zoom-in">
                <img decoding="async" width="1200" height="795" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/tremors16.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full" alt="Still from Tremors" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/tremors16.jpg 1200w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/tremors16-300x199.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/tremors16-640x424.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/tremors16-768x509.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/tremors16-980x649.jpg 980w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px">
              </a>
              <div class="pswp-caption-content" id="caption-1643287">
                Earl and Val realize the threat is underground.
                                  <div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit">
                    Credit:
                                          Universal Pictures 
                                      </div>
                              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
                  </div>
                  <figcaption>
          <div class="caption font-impact mb-4 mt-2 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-base leading-tight text-gray-300">
    <div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_5px] w-[10px] shrink-0"></div>
    <div class="caption-content">
      Earl and Val realize the threat is underground.

              <span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs">
          Credit:

          
          Universal Pictures 

                  </span>
          </div>
  </div>
        </figcaption>
            </figure>

<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tremor_(disambiguation)"><em>Tremors</em></a> is an <a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2020/01/tremors-turns-30-the-most-perfect-b-movie-creature-feature-ever-made/">unabashed love letter</a> to the B-movie creature features of the 1950s that remains as fresh today as it was over three decades ago. The film is sheer perfection and ranks among my personal favorite films of all time. The story takes place in the tiny fictional desert town of Perfection, Nevada—population 15, at least at the start of the film. But something begins killing the residents (and the livestock). Director Ron Underwood set the narrative up like a mystery, introducing us to the main characters and setting as they realize the threat that is coming for them: subterranean monsters dubbed "graboids."</p>
<p><em>Tremors</em> has a terrific cast of characters, played by gifted actors. But it's the ingenious design of the graboids that really makes the film for me—how the characters figure out the monsters' characteristics. Above all, the graboids are smart and capable of learning about their human prey and adapting accordingly. When humans hide in a car, they dig around the surrounding soil so the whole vehicle sinks underground. They do the same thing to loosen building foundations when the residents take refuge on their roofs. They dig a trap just as the humans are almost safely to the mountains, and so forth. The humans have to keep upping their game to survive, and the ingenious ways they outwit the monsters is a huge part of the film's delight.</p>
<h2><em>Scream</em> (1996)</h2>
<figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2058898 align-none">
    <div>
                        <div class="ars-lightbox">
            <div class="ars-lightbox-item">
              <a data-pswp-width="1200" data-pswp-height="801" data-pswp-srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror11A-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror11A-640x427.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror11A-768x513.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror11A-980x654.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror11A.jpg 1200w" data-cropped="true" href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror11A.jpg" target="_blank" class="cursor-zoom-in">
                <img decoding="async" width="1200" height="801" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror11A.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full" alt="blonde woman with pageboy haircut holding phone to her ear while screaming in terror" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror11A.jpg 1200w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror11A-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror11A-640x427.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror11A-768x513.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror11A-980x654.jpg 980w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px">
              </a>
              <div class="pswp-caption-content" id="caption-2058898">
                
                                  <div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit">
                    Credit:
                                          Dimension Films
                                      </div>
                              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
                  </div>
                  <figcaption>
          <div class="caption font-impact mb-4 mt-2 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-base leading-tight text-gray-300">
    <div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_7px] w-[10px] shrink-0"></div>
    <div class="caption-content">
      

              <span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs">
          Credit:

          
          Dimension Films

                  </span>
          </div>
  </div>
        </figcaption>
            </figure>

<p>No horror comedy list would be complete without including the oh-so-meta <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scream_(1996_film)"><em>Scream</em></a>, which introduced the costumed serial killer Ghostface to the world. <em>Scream</em> deftly deconstructs the slasher genre and its surprisingly moralistic "rules," helpfully defined by horror fan Randy (Jamie Kennedy): no drinking, doing drugs, or having sex—the Final Girl, Sidney (Neve Campbell), is naturally a virgin—and also never, ever leave your friend group and tell them you'll "be right back." (You won't.) Naturally, all of these rules are broken by one character or another, with the expected bloody results.</p>

          
                  </div>

              </div>

      
      <div class="hidden min-w-[300px] justify-self-end bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-50 lg:block">
        
                  <div class="ad-wrapper is-sticky is-rail">
        <div class="ad-wrapper-inner">
            <div class="ad ad--rail"></div>
        </div>
    </div>
              </div>
    </div>
                    
        <div class="ad-wrapper with-label is-fullwidth">
        <div class="ad-wrapper-inner">
            <div class="ad ad--mid-content">
          </div>
        </div>
    </div>
          
    
    <div class="mx-auto my-2.5 px-[15px] sm:px-5 lg:grid lg:max-w-5xl lg:grid-cols-3 lg:gap-6 lg:px-8 xl:px-0">
      <div class="relative lg:col-span-2">

        
        <div class="post-content post-content-double">
          
          
<p>The humor is self-referential without being parody; the performances are strong; and the jump scares and horror tributes are plentiful (Linda Blair of <em>The Exorcist</em> fame makes a cameo). Those elements helped the film tap into the cultural zeitgeist of the mid-1990s, blasting past low box office projections to gross $173 million worldwide. <em>Scream</em> has spawned multiple sequels, an anthology film series, and the <em>Scary Movie</em> horror parody franchise, revitalizing what was at the time a stagnating market for horror. It's now widely viewed as one of the most influential horror movies of all time.</p>
<div class="page-anchor-wrapper"><a class="record-pageview" name="page-3" data-page="3" data-url="https://arstechnica.com/culture/2024/10/celebrate-halloween-with-20-of-our-favorite-horror-comedies/"></a></div>
<h2><em>Shaun of the Dead</em> (2004)</h2>
<figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2058901 align-none">
    <div>
                        <div class="ars-lightbox">
            <div class="ars-lightbox-item">
              <a data-pswp-width="1200" data-pswp-height="805" data-pswp-srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dead8-300x201.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dead8-640x429.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dead8-768x515.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dead8-980x657.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dead8.jpg 1200w" data-cropped="true" href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dead8.jpg" target="_blank" class="cursor-zoom-in">
                <img decoding="async" width="1200" height="805" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dead8.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full" alt="group of people running away from zombies" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dead8.jpg 1200w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dead8-300x201.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dead8-640x429.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dead8-768x515.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/dead8-980x657.jpg 980w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px">
              </a>
              <div class="pswp-caption-content" id="caption-2058901">
                
                                  <div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit">
                    Credit:
                                          Universal Pictures
                                      </div>
                              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
                  </div>
                  <figcaption>
          <div class="caption font-impact mb-4 mt-2 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-base leading-tight text-gray-300">
    <div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_7px] w-[10px] shrink-0"></div>
    <div class="caption-content">
      

              <span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs">
          Credit:

          
          Universal Pictures

                  </span>
          </div>
  </div>
        </figcaption>
            </figure>

<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shaun_of_the_Dead"><em>Shaun of the Dead</em></a> is the first film in Simon Pegg's <em>Three Flavors Cornetto</em> trilogy, in which Pegg's Shaun, a mild-mannered slacker London salesman, finds himself caught up in a zombie apocalypse and must rise to the occasion to save his friends and family. That includes his best friend Ed (Nick Frost), girlfriend Liz (Kate Ashfield), mom Barbara (Penelope Wilton), and stepdad Philip (Bill Nighy), as well as Liz's roommates, David (Dylan Moran) and Diane (Lucy Davis).</p>
<p>Shaun is an unlikely hero; Liz has broken up with him because he's unambitious and spends all his free time playing video games with Ed or hanging out at the Winchester pub. The film is about this everyman finding his inner hero. He and Ed hurl vinyl records at a pair of zombies—pausing to quibble over which ones they should preserve—and take out even more brain-eaters with cricket bats. At one point the crew pretends to be zombies to make their way to the Winchester for a final showdown. But their little group is wildly outnumbered, and while<em> Shaun of the Dead</em> is very funny with its distinctively British humor, it's also sometimes downright heartbreaking. That's a fine line to navigate, and Pegg does so exceptionally well.</p>
<h2><em>Zombieland</em> (2009)</h2>
<figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2058905 align-none">
    <div>
                        <div class="ars-lightbox">
            <div class="ars-lightbox-item">
              <a data-pswp-width="1200" data-pswp-height="810" data-pswp-srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror12-300x203.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror12-640x432.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror12-768x518.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror12-980x662.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror12.jpg 1200w" data-cropped="true" href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror12.jpg" target="_blank" class="cursor-zoom-in">
                <img decoding="async" width="1200" height="810" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror12.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full" alt="young nerdy man and tough older man in cowboy hat, both holding rifles at the ready in case of zombies" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror12.jpg 1200w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror12-300x203.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror12-640x432.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror12-768x518.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror12-980x662.jpg 980w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px">
              </a>
              <div class="pswp-caption-content" id="caption-2058905">
                
                                  <div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit">
                    Credit:
                                          Sony Pictures
                                      </div>
                              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
                  </div>
                  <figcaption>
          <div class="caption font-impact mb-4 mt-2 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-base leading-tight text-gray-300">
    <div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_7px] w-[10px] shrink-0"></div>
    <div class="caption-content">
      

              <span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs">
          Credit:

          
          Sony Pictures

                  </span>
          </div>
  </div>
        </figcaption>
            </figure>

<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombieland"><em>Zombieland</em></a> is America's answer to <em>Shaun of the Dead</em>: a fresh, fun take on the "<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zombie_comedy">zom-com</a>" format. A virulent form of human-adapted mad cow disease sweeps across the United States, transforming most of the nation’s populace into ravenous zombies. The film follows a ragtag group of unlikely survivors—Columbus (Jesse Eisenberg), Tallahassee (Woody Harrelson), and orphaned sisters Wichita (Emma Stone) and Little Rock (Abigail Breslin)—on a road trip in hopes of finding some place yet untouched by the disease, ending with a pitched battle against zombie hordes in an abandoned amusement park.</p>

          
                  </div>

              </div>

      
      <div class="hidden min-w-[300px] justify-self-end bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-50 lg:block">
        
                  <div class="ad-wrapper is-sticky is-rail">
        <div class="ad-wrapper-inner">
            <div class="ad ad--rail"></div>
        </div>
    </div>
              </div>
    </div>
                    
        <div class="ad-wrapper with-label is-fullwidth">
        <div class="ad-wrapper-inner">
            <div class="ad ad--mid-content">
          </div>
        </div>
    </div>
          
    
    <div class="mx-auto my-2.5 px-[15px] sm:px-5 lg:grid lg:max-w-5xl lg:grid-cols-3 lg:gap-6 lg:px-8 xl:px-0">
      <div class="relative lg:col-span-2">

        
        <div class="post-content post-content-double">
          
          
<p>It's a fun mix of horror and dark screwball comedy, especially the "Zombie Kills of the Week" and Columbus' hilarious <a href="http://www.zombielandrules.com/all-zombieland-rules/">survival rules</a>—cardio, limber up, beware of bathrooms, and buckle up, for instance, not to mention the "double tap"—often illustrated by various doomed souls who failed to heed those rules. Bill Murray's star turn playing himself just might rank as one of the best surprise cameos of all time. The 2019 sequel, <a href="https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2019/10/review-zombieland-double-tap-delivers-wise-cracking-brain-splattering-fun/"><em>Zombieland: Double Tap</em></a>, didn't quite hit the same high marks, but the pair still make for a terrific double feature.</p>
<h2><em>Trollhunter</em> (2010)</h2>
<figure class="ars-img-shortcode id-2058907 align-none">
    <div>
                        <div class="ars-lightbox">
            <div class="ars-lightbox-item">
              <a data-pswp-width="1200" data-pswp-height="800" data-pswp-srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror13-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror13-640x427.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror13-768x512.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror13-980x653.jpg 980w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror13.jpg 1200w" data-cropped="true" href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror13.jpg" target="_blank" class="cursor-zoom-in">
                <img decoding="async" width="1200" height="800" src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror13.jpg" class="attachment-full size-full" alt="giant troll standing on Norwegian plain at dusk" srcset="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror13.jpg 1200w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror13-300x200.jpg 300w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror13-640x427.jpg 640w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror13-768x512.jpg 768w, https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/horror13-980x653.jpg 980w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px">
              </a>
              <div class="pswp-caption-content" id="caption-2058907">
                
                                  <div class="ars-gallery-caption-credit">
                    Credit:
                                          SF Norge A/S
                                      </div>
                              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
                  </div>
                  <figcaption>
          <div class="caption font-impact mb-4 mt-2 inline-flex flex-row items-stretch gap-1 text-base leading-tight text-gray-300">
    <div class="caption-icon bg-[left_top_7px] w-[10px] shrink-0"></div>
    <div class="caption-content">
      

              <span class="caption-credit mt-2 whitespace-nowrap text-xs">
          Credit:

          
          SF Norge A/S

                  </span>
          </div>
  </div>
        </figcaption>
            </figure>

<p>This quirky Norwegian offering is shot in the style of a found footage mockumentary. A group of college students set off into the wilds of the fjord land to make a documentary about a suspected bear poacher named Hans, played by Norwegian comedian Otto Jesperson. They discover that Hans and another hunter named Finn (Hans Morten Hansen) are actually hunting down trolls and decide to document those endeavors instead. They soon realize they are very much out of their depth.</p>
<p>Writer/director André Øvredal infuses <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trollhunter"><em>Trollhunter</em></a> with myriad references to Norwegian culture, especially its folklore and fairy tales surrounding trolls. There are woodland trolls and mountain trolls, some with tails, some with multiple heads. They turn to stone when exposed to sunlight—which is why one of the troll hunters carries around a powerful UV lamp—and mostly eat rocks but can develop a taste for human flesh, and they can smell the blood of a Christian. The film is peppered with dry wit rather than laugh-out-loud moments, and non-Norwegians might miss some of the cultural in-jokes. But Øvredal masterfully builds suspense and a creeping sense of dread, plus there's all that gorgeous footage of the Norwegian landscape to delight viewers around the world.</p>

          
                  </div>

              </div>

      
      <div class="hidden min-w-[300px] justify-self-end bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-50 lg:block">
        
                  <div class="ad-wrapper is-sticky is-rail">
        <div class="ad-wrapper-inner">
            <div class="ad ad--rail"></div>
        </div>
